[{"age": null, "album": "", "artist": null, "bookmarked": false, "comments": [], "date_published": "2024-08-21T23:00:08+00:00", "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"A screenshot from the Megalopolis trailer\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/-HSQdWmphq8JGgsDUZyXoWUKQ6A=/251x0:2393x1428/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73536583/megaopolis_trailer.0.png\" />\n        <figcaption><em>A screenshot from the </em>Megalopolis <em>trailer.</em> | Image: Lionsgate</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"4MRPla\">Hours after it was released, Lionsgate pulled a trailer for <em>Megalopolis </em>that was clearly \u201c<a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2024/8/21/24225219/megalopolis-new-trailer-is-gunning-for-the-haters\">gunning for the haters</a>\u201d with a selection of negative quotes about director Francis Ford Coppola\u2019s previous works. That\u2019s because reports like <a href=\"https://www.vulture.com/article/did-the-megalopolis-trailer-make-up-fake-movie-critic-quotes.html\">this one from <em>Vulture\u2019s</em> Bilge Ebiri</a> showed that critic quotes in the trailer lambasting films like <em>The Godfather</em> and <em>Apocalypse Now", "id": 1039941, "language": "en-US", "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/8/21/24225673/megalopolis-trailer-fake-quotes-movie-critics-pulled", "manual_status_code": 0, "page_rating": 27, "page_rating_contents": 86, "page_rating_visits": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "permanent": false, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "source_obj__id": 359, "status_code": 0, "tags": [], "thumbnail": null, "title": "The bad movie reviews quoted in Lionsgate\u2019s Megalopolis trailer were mostly made up", "user": null, "vote": 0}, {"age": null, "album": "", "artist": null, "bookmarked": false, "comments": [], "date_published": "2024-08-21T21:06:35+00:00", "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"The image displays Apple\u2019s blue App Store logo in front of a pink and black background.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/K1gSb22K4jM9TyQbU77iv1G_3YI=/0x0:3000x2000/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73536347/acastro_STK045_03.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Illustration by Alex Castro / The Verge</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"F53Gn2\">Apple is splitting its App Store division in half, <a href=\"https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-08-21/apple-s-app-store-head-to-leave-in-reorganization-amid-global-scrutiny\">according to a report from <em>Bloomberg</em></a>. While one group of employees will run the App Store, the other will manage its approach to alternative marketplaces that have started opening up in the European Union.</p>\n<p id=\"74cnrD\">As part of the change, App Store vice president Matt Fischer will leave the company after more than a decade in the role. \u201cThis has been on my mind for some time, and as we are also reorgani", "id": 1039942, "language": "en-US", "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/8/21/24225566/apple-app-store-matt-fischer-stepping-down", "manual_status_code": 0, "page_rating": 27, "page_rating_contents": 86, "page_rating_visits": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "permanent": false, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "source_obj__id": 359, "status_code": 0, "tags": [], "thumbnail": null, "title": "Apple is shaking up how it manages the App Store", "user": null, "vote": 0}, {"age": null, "album": "", "artist": null, "bookmarked": false, "comments": [], "date_published": "2024-08-21T20:30:46+00:00", "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"A Chick-fil-A restaurant.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/AC3G2h_jQeK-xxkxw8F1xeiOzDI=/104x58:1336x879/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73536261/Chick_fil_a.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Image: Chick-fil-A</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"s8HwES\">The <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2023/10/28/23934629/streaming-price-hikes-netflix-hulu-disney-plus-expensive\">streaming space has become so crowded</a> that it\u2019s hard to imagine why any company would want to break in now, but that is apparently what Chick-fil-A (yes, the fast food chain) is planning to do.</p>\n<p id=\"TgOQSS\"><em>Deadline</em> reports that <a href=\"https://deadline.com/2024/08/chick-fil-a-hatches-streaming-service-1236044196/\">Chick-fil-A is working with a number of production companies and traditional studios</a> to create multiple original shows for a streaming platform debuting sometime later this year. Initially, the restaurant is said to be focused on family-frie", "id": 1039943, "language": "en-US", "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/8/21/24225507/chick-fil-a-streaming-service", "manual_status_code": 0, "page_rating": 27, "page_rating_contents": 86, "page_rating_visits": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "permanent": false, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "source_obj__id": 359, "status_code": 0, "tags": [], "thumbnail": null, "title": "Chick-fil-A is reportedly launching a streaming service for some reason", "user": null, "vote": 0}, {"age": null, "album": "", "artist": null, "bookmarked": false, "comments": [], "date_published": "2024-08-21T20:25:36+00:00", "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"Silver GMC truck in a garage with a kayak on the wall and a person holding the charge plug on the side of the truck\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/3U8VDO4ENeGb8nq6m2btfGDX2Tw=/0x0:2484x1656/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73536246/2024_gmc_sierra_ev_edition_1_015.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Image: GMC</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"VYTc1E\">GMC says its limited \u201cDenali Edition 1\u201d launch versions of the new Sierra EV pickup truck <a href=\"https://pressroom.gmc.com/gmbx/us/en/gmc/pressroom/news.detail.html/Pages/news/us/en/2024/aug/0821-gmcsierradenaliev.html\">are now being delivered to their first customers</a> and are available for purchase at dealerships nationwide.</p>\n<p id=\"smYr4J\">GMC\u2019s 2024 Sierra EV is parent company GM\u2019s third electric pickup truck built on the Ultium EV platform after the just-launched Chevy Silverado EV. It\u2019s also GM\u2019s second GMC-branded EV after the beastly Hummer EV pickup (which now <a href=\"https", "id": 1039944, "language": "en-US", "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/8/21/24225451/gmc-sierra-ev-denali-edition-1-launch-delivery", "manual_status_code": 0, "page_rating": 27, "page_rating_contents": 86, "page_rating_visits": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "permanent": false, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "source_obj__id": 359, "status_code": 0, "tags": [], "thumbnail": null, "title": "GMC is delivering its first Sierra EV electric pickup trucks to customers", "user": null, "vote": 0}, {"age": null, "album": "", "artist": null, "bookmarked": false, "comments": [], "date_published": "2024-08-21T20:20:40+00:00", "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"US-VOTE-POLITICS-DEMOCRATIC-CONVENTION\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/tpTh8PXYChv6mBvV3U-haeeLiSA=/0x0:6706x4471/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73536234/2166924268.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption><em>Lil Jon joins the Georgia delegation at the DNC roll call to raucous applause.</em> | Photo by Mandel Ngan / AFP via Getty Images</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"kipBQu\">Compare clips from the Democratic National Convention, which kicked off on Monday in Chicago, to the Republican National Convention in July. They feel like different universes.</p>\n<p id=\"WaYxJt\">At the RNC, during the roll call of votes nominating Donald Trump, states were called out to scattered applause along with the number of votes. The room was mostly quiet, and it sounded more like a jury delivering bad news than it did a political party affirming its future.</p>\n<p id=\"hDm2sX\">The DNC roll call, meanwhile, included <a href=\"https://www.npr.org/2024/08/21/g-s1", "id": 1039945, "language": "en-US", "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/8/21/24225330/democratic-national-convention-tiktok-content-creators-nielsen-ratings", "manual_status_code": 0, "page_rating": 27, "page_rating_contents": 86, "page_rating_visits": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "permanent": false, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "source_obj__id": 359, "status_code": 0, "tags": [], "thumbnail": null, "title": "With the DNC, Democrats finally understand that content is king", "user": null, "vote": 0}, {"age": null, "album": "", "artist": null, "bookmarked": false, "comments": [], "date_published": "2024-08-21T19:27:03+00:00", "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"President Joe Biden\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/pv2wirGLuvlX30gHig9G4PBdbpE=/0x0:8256x5504/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73536117/2167497235.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Photo by Brandon Bell / Getty Images</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"XwIWUu\">A telecom company that transmitted the <a href=\"https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2024-election/fake-joe-biden-robocall-tells-new-hampshire-democrats-not-vote-tuesday-rcna134984\">deepfake robocall of President Joe Biden\u2019s voice</a> has agreed to pay $1 million to resolve an enforcement action from the Federal Communications Commission, the agency announced.</p>\n<p id=\"efzTiI\">Lingo Telecom relayed a fake Biden message to New Hampshire voters in January, urging them not to turn out for the Democratic primary. The FCC identified political consultant Steve Kramer as the person behind the generative AI calls and <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2024/5/23/24163411/fcc-fine-biden-deepfa", "id": 1037890, "language": "en-US", "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/8/21/24225435/lingo-telecom-biden-deepfake-robocall-fcc-fine", "manual_status_code": 0, "page_rating": 27, "page_rating_contents": 86, "page_rating_visits": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "permanent": false, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "source_obj__id": 359, "status_code": 0, "tags": [], "thumbnail": null, "title": "Telecom will pay $1 million over deepfake Joe Biden robocall", "user": null, "vote": 0}, {"age": null, "album": "", "artist": null, "bookmarked": false, "comments": [], "date_published": "2024-08-21T19:22:05+00:00", "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"A crane lifts a worker up to a utility pole to repair power lines.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/-M0ezfqFd7SFosqhQg4ws2HQ7mY=/0x0:4900x3267/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73536101/2161768766.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption><em>A line worker tends to fallen power lines in the East End neighborhood of Houston, days after Hurricane Beryl made landfall, on Thursday, July 11th, 2024. </em> | Raquel Natalicchio / Houston Chronicle via Getty Images</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"4DpOlN\">The US has dealt with 60 percent more weather-related outages during warmer months over the past decade than it did during the 2000s, according to <a href=\"https://www.climatecentral.org/climate-matters/heat-season-power-outages\">data crunched by the nonprofit research organization Climate Central</a>. </p>\n<p id=\"r2UG1K\">It\u2019s a trend that raises health risks as the planet heats up. Climate change <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2021/8/9/22613531/cli", "id": 1037891, "language": "en-US", "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/8/21/24225417/weather-power-outages-summer-data-analysis", "manual_status_code": 0, "page_rating": 27, "page_rating_contents": 86, "page_rating_visits": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "permanent": false, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "source_obj__id": 359, "status_code": 0, "tags": [], "thumbnail": null, "title": "Summer blackouts are increasing in the US", "user": null, "vote": 0}, {"age": null, "album": "", "artist": null, "bookmarked": false, "comments": [], "date_published": "2024-08-21T19:02:34+00:00", "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"Twitch logo against a pink and purple backdrop\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/aEc64sP6wwF_S8Enqkf88FPgwLk=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73536035/STK044_VRG_Illo_N_Barclay_1_twitch.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Illustration by Nick Barclay / The Verge</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"GHBAUk\">If you subscribe to Twitch channels from Twitch\u2019s mobile app, you might have to pay a bit more starting in October.</p>\n<p id=\"I9kRYn\">Twitch announced on Wednesday that Tier 1 and gift subscriptions in more than 40 countries will have a higher price on the mobile app <a href=\"https://x.com/TwitchSupport/status/1826296039533400460\">starting on October 1st</a>. According to emails from Twitch shared <a href=\"https://www.dexerto.com/twitch/twitch-users-devastated-as-streaming-platform-raises-sub-prices-yet-again-2871813/\">by <em>Dexerto</em></a> and <a href=\"https://www.reddit.com/r/Twitch/comments/1exulg4/this_is_pathetic/\">on ", "id": 1037892, "language": "en-US", "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/8/21/24225463/twitch-subscription-price-increase-mobile-web", "manual_status_code": 0, "page_rating": 27, "page_rating_contents": 86, "page_rating_visits": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "permanent": false, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "source_obj__id": 359, "status_code": 0, "tags": [], "thumbnail": null, "title": "Twitch is upping subscription prices on mobile", "user": null, "vote": 0}, {"age": null, "album": "", "artist": null, "bookmarked": false, "comments": [], "date_published": "2024-08-21T18:20:36+00:00", "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"Handing holding up a credit card with colorful illustrations of money, banks, and finance apps in the background.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/Q3Jg1lL_YLfUHGFmYQDlMq_wMu4=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73535934/HT017_money_0007.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Illustration by Samar Haddad / The Verge</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"ffJnlu\">Back in 2017,  <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2017/9/22/16345580/equifax-data-breach-credit-identity-theft-updates\">Equifax announced</a> that hackers stole half of the US population\u2019s Social Security numbers in what, we said, \u201cwill likely end up being one of the worst data breaches to ever affect the country.\u201d Perhaps \u2014 until this year, when about 2.9 billion rows of data were collected through <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2024/8/16/24222112/data-breach-national-public-data-2-9-billion-ssn\">a breach at National Public Data (NPD)</a>, a company that resells collected per", "id": 1037893, "language": "en-US", "link": "https://www.theverge.com/24224789/data-breach-freeze-report-security-how-to", "manual_status_code": 0, "page_rating": 27, "page_rating_contents": 86, "page_rating_visits": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "permanent": false, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "source_obj__id": 359, "status_code": 0, "tags": [], "thumbnail": null, "title": "How to freeze your credit after a data breach", "user": null, "vote": 0}, {"age": null, "album": "", "artist": null, "bookmarked": false, "comments": [], "date_published": "2024-08-21T18:16:54+00:00", "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/YKq-X5MEcpff2E0J0d39YdXfMb4=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73535929/acastro_171108_1777_0009_v3.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Illustration by Alex Castro / The Verge</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"Qp80Nq\">AI-enabled ammunition vending machines could facilitate mass shootings and let people circumvent federal bans prohibiting people with certain criminal convictions from buying ammunition, two senators warn.</p>\n<p id=\"yi9q33\">Massachusetts Senators Ed Markey and Elizabeth Warren sent a <a href=\"https://www.markey.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/letter_to_atf_on_ammunition_vending_machines.pdf\">letter</a> to the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives (ATF) asking it to \u201cclosely examine\u201d facial recognition-enabled <a href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2024/07/12/us/vending-machines-ammunition-alabama-texas-oklahoma/index.html\">ammunition vending machines</a> that have recently been ins", "id": 1037894, "language": "en-US", "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/8/21/24225431/ammunition-vending-machines-atf-markey-warren-letter-american-rounds", "manual_status_code": 0, "page_rating": 27, "page_rating_contents": 86, "page_rating_visits": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "permanent": false, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "source_obj__id": 359, "status_code": 0, "tags": [], "thumbnail": null, "title": "Senators want investigation of AI-enabled ammo vending machines", "user": null, "vote": 0}, {"age": null, "album": "", "artist": null, "bookmarked": false, "comments": [], "date_published": "2024-08-21T18:08:30+00:00", "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"An illustration of the Google logo.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/LakRTbr4QAnrdr4Uh7yKY_GkGIk=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73535917/STK093_Google_02.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Illustration: The Verge</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"legRoQ\">Google representatives gave ad buyers tips on how they could reach teens, even though the company bars targeted advertisements to users under the age of 18 based on their demographics, according to <a href=\"https://www.adweek.com/programmatic/exclusive-google-suggests-buyers-target-teens-going-against-its-policies/\">a report from <em>Adweek</em></a>. </p>\n<p id=\"5I80BO\">Three unnamed ad buyers told <em>Adweek</em> that Google sales reps suggested they might be able to reach teens by targeting <a href=\"https://support.google.com/google-ads/answer/2580383?hl=en\">a group of \u201cunknown\u201d users</a>, whose \u201cage, gender, parental status, or household income\u201d Google doesn\u2019t know. <e", "id": 1037895, "language": "en-US", "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/8/21/24225326/google-target-teens-ads-unknown-users", "manual_status_code": 0, "page_rating": 27, "page_rating_contents": 86, "page_rating_visits": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "permanent": false, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "source_obj__id": 359, "status_code": 0, "tags": [], "thumbnail": null, "title": "Google sales reps allegedly keep telling advertisers how to target teens", "user": null, "vote": 0}, {"age": null, "album": "", "artist": null, "bookmarked": false, "comments": [], "date_published": "2024-08-21T17:57:43+00:00", "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"Illustration of Windows Recall\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/hJSg-17Fk38ACi7_PXJwG0CBgjQ=/0x0:1320x880/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73535822/windowsrecall.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Image: Microsoft</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"pJTR8z\">Microsoft says it\u2019s planning to allow Windows testers to try out its controversial Recall AI feature in October. The software giant was originally planning to launch Recall with its Copilot Plus PCs in June but was <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2024/6/13/24178144/microsoft-windows-ai-recall-feature-delay\">forced to hold back the feature</a> after security concerns were raised. </p>\n<p id=\"mXnU5L\">At the time of the delay on June 13th, Microsoft promised the feature \u2014 that screenshots nearly everything on your PC \u2014  would be available for Windows Insiders \u201cin the coming weeks,\u201d but that\u2019s now more like the coming months. \u201cWith a commitment to delivering a trustworthy and secure Recall", "id": 1037896, "language": "en-US", "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/8/21/24225439/microsoft-recall-windows-ai-feature-october-testing", "manual_status_code": 0, "page_rating": 27, "page_rating_contents": 86, "page_rating_visits": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "permanent": false, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "source_obj__id": 359, "status_code": 0, "tags": [], "thumbnail": null, "title": "Microsoft\u2019s Recall AI feature won\u2019t be available for Windows testers until October", "user": null, "vote": 0}, {"age": null, "album": "", "artist": null, "bookmarked": false, "comments": [], "date_published": "2024-08-21T17:41:52+00:00", "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/nhd5VoV5CqrssSPR_tWzbgKxNm0=/0x0:3435x2290/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73535751/IMG_1210.0.jpeg\" />\n        <figcaption>Image: Umar Shakir / The Verge</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"NMm0I3\">Tesla is <a href=\"https://www.nhtsa.gov/?nhtsaId=24V615000\">issuing a new recall</a> for more than 9,000 of its Model X SUVs due to roof cosmetic trim pieces that could fly off while driving because they may have been adhered without primer. It\u2019s the second such recall from the company to address the issue on the Model X, <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2020/11/25/21719586/tesla-recall-2016-cars-model-x-y-manufacturing-issues\">the first one issued in 2020</a>, and it is again specific to early 2016 vehicle models.</p>\n<p id=\"p1bnpo\">Tesla often pushes software updates to address recalls, including <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2024/4/26/24141403/tesla-autopilot-nhtsa-investigation-recall-software-fix", "id": 1037897, "language": "en-US", "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/8/21/24225309/tesla-model-x-second-recall-roof-trim-adhesive", "manual_status_code": 0, "page_rating": 27, "page_rating_contents": 86, "page_rating_visits": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "permanent": false, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "source_obj__id": 359, "status_code": 0, "tags": [], "thumbnail": null, "title": "Tesla\u2019s latest Model X recall isn\u2019t just a software update", "user": null, "vote": 0}, {"age": null, "album": "", "artist": null, "bookmarked": false, "comments": [], "date_published": "2024-08-21T17:00:00+00:00", 